1.title: Potato Sprouts
1.plot: Rusty the Ant, finds himself a potato in the dumpster. Cosmo the Fly Joe Croaker the Frog, snatch Rusty's potato in the middle of the night. Joe and Cosmo decide to bury the potato in the soil to keep it safe. Rusty returns to them every day and questions them about the location of the potato. But the two insist that they don't know anything about it. One day Joe Croaker is hungry and decides to dig up the potato. Although, the potato appears to have sprouted, the frog and fly start feasting on the growing potato. Joe and Cosmo become very ill after their meal. Bartle...

2.title: A Thunderstorm
2.plot: Joe Croaker enjoys the same rain that is scaring the rest of the bugs in the mars. That is, until the lightning comes.

3.title: Bending Time
3.plot: When Joe Croaker demands birthday gifts from all the bugs in the marsh, Bartle Bee decided he need to be taught a lesson. They trick him and Cosmo into thinking an ordinary alarm clock they have has the power to bend time itself.

4.title: A Weevil Comes to the Marsh
4.plot: When a new bug comes to the marsh, the other bugs are less than inviting. That is, until he defends them against the evil frog, Joe Croaker.

5.title: A Cicada's Trouble
5.plot: When the gang meets a Cicada with a sad story about being alone all his life, they vow to help him overcome his issues by teaching him to embrace who he really is.

6.title: Bugs Hate Cell Phones
6.plot: When a cell phone is found at the marsh, Joe Croaker claims it as his property, and doesn't let anyone else play with it, no matter how hard they try.

7.title: A Mole Cricket
7.plot: Joe Croaker throws himself into an intensive bodybuilding program. But the racket he creates is very disturbing to his underground neighbor, Mr. Mole Cricket. So when the mild-mannered mole cricket finds he cannot get Joe Croaker to quiet down, he decides to teach the cocky frog a lesson.

8.title: A Dancing Cocoon
8.plot: While buzzing about The Marsh, Bartle Bee is amazed to find a "dancing" bean among the flowers. Bartle Bee enjoys immensely his new discovery, unaware that Cosmo the Fly is looking on, angling for a chance to swipe the little bean and run. Eventually he succeeds, then spirits the bean back to the pond, where he and Joe Croaker try to cajole it into dancing for them.

9.title: The Fun with Shadows
9.plot: When the dung beetle, Mc Broom, is scared of his own shadow, it's up to the rest of the bugs in the marsh to get him over his fears.

10.title: The Master of Camouflage
10.plot: There is an intruder in the Marsh. A new insect that no one seems to be able to locate. Is everyone going crazy, or is there really a master of camouflage in the marsh?

11.title: The Secret in the Ball
11.plot: When Bartle Bee and Flutterby finish their house cleaning and are appreciating their work, a foul smell on the wind comes along to ruin their mood. They follow the smell to McBroom's house, which is full of the stinky dung balls. McBroom is not at home but both Bartle Bee and Flutterby can't wait. They start to clean McBroom's place without asking his permission.

12.title: Croaker Needs Some Help
12.plot: Joe Croaker finds a magnet in the grass, and convinces himself he has found a precious stone. He shows off his find to Cosmo, who wants the curious object for himself. But Joe's not willing to give it up.

13.title: Eat Only What You Know!
13.plot: Both Bartle Bee and Joe Croaker are thrilled to see a large number of mushrooms emerge after a rain. Among them is a big, brightly-colored one, and Joe Croaker imagines it to be quite delicious. So he wolfs down the whole fungus, despite Bartle Bee's warning that eating unfamiliar fungi can be dangerous. Soon Joe Croaker begins to hallucinate, and the frenzied frog's actions present a real threat to the whole ecosystem centered around the pond.

14.title: Who's Stinging?
14.plot: A female mosquito spots Joe Croaker and bites him when the frog is napping under a big tree. She makes the most out of the opportunity and bites him as many times as possible but the pain and noise soon wake Joe up. The irritated Joe begins to chase the mosquito and he's determined that this pest will pay. In the mean time, the mosquito's brother is out looking for her and he comes across Joe Croaker at an in-opportune time.

15.title: Burden or Blessing?
15.plot: A snail comes to the Marsh and is really disappointed at seeing Bartle Bee and his friends fly elegantly and freely in the air. And he blames his shell, which he thinks is a real burden and stops him from doing fun things. And though Cosmo and Joe Croaker pick on him, the rest of the bugs are determined to help him out.

16.title: The Incredible Seedlings
16.plot: When the gang discovers the potential strength of a sprouting seedling (compared to the insects), they use one to help them make their lives a little easier.

17.title: The Antennae of Cosmo
17.plot: Bartle Bee notices that whenever and wherever he is enjoying his honey, the little fly Cosmo always manages to find him and asks if he'd like to share. Cosmo tells him it's all because of his incredible antennae.

18.title: An Amazing Transformation
18.plot: When Joe finds a caterpillar in the marsh, he adopts it. But soon after he grows tires of it and passes it to the next bug for safe keeping. This continues until it turns into a butterfly, much to everyone's surprise.

19.title: The Strategy of Pipevines
19.plot: When Strobe entrusts Bartle Bee to watch his brother Sparkle so he can do some "real" work, it isn't long before Sparkle goes missing. And the gang better find him soon, because he has fallen into the dreaded Pipe Vine plant.

20.title: Exploding Cucumbers
20.plot: It's exploding cucumber season and they are ripe for the picking. But a few unwanted grasshoppers are not about to let these other bugs enjoy all the juice for themselves.

21.title: The Monster in the Tunnel
21.plot: The ant, Rusty, is out searching for food when he encounters a "tunnel". He says "hey" to the tunnel and the same "hey" comes echoing back to him. Thinking there is someone trapped inside, Rusty decides to do some exploring. Soon, he gets hims self lost, and it's up to the rest of the gang to get him out without getting lost themselves.

22.title: A Courageous Pill-Bug
22.plot: Bartle comes across a pill-bug, also known as Rollie-pollie. This Rollie-Pollie is a very timid and elusive insect. When Bartle first spots him, he is struggling to get down a rock that stands barely an inch from the ground. Bartle introduces himself to Rollie and decides to help Rollie by turning this always nervous bug brave.

23.title: Where's the Bean?
23.plot: When Cosmo the fly finds a special bean, he must hide it before anyone else finds out about it, especially Joe Croaker... But where did he hide it again?

24.title: A Leaf Mantis
24.plot: There is a prankster in the marsh, and good-luck finding him. As a master of disguise, the leaf-mantis can do whatever he wants and simply "disappear". But when he need the help of the other insects of the marsh, he'd better hope they are as forgiving as he is mischievous.

25.title: A Weather Forecaster
25.plot: When a weather forecasting pine moth comes into town and shows off his forecasting skills, some insects are impressed, some... not so much.

26.title: The High Jump Champion
26.plot: An overly friendly flea visits the marsh and with the help of his amazing jumping skills, helps the other insects with random tasks. but not everyone is impressed by his super powers.

27.title: Joe Croaker and His Spring Shoe
27.plot: Bartle Bee and Flutterby are sitting on the top of a tree, enjoying the great view of sunset. This makes the frog Joe really jealous. Joe tries really hard to climb up the tree, but he simply can not make it up to the top. Will springs attached to his feet help?

28.title: Confined in the New Home
28.plot: It's winter in the Marsh and everyone is feeling the effects. Joe Croaker decides that living in a mason jar is his best bet. It works well enough, and he refuses to share with anyone else. But when he tries to get our, he finds himself stuck. Now he must look to the same bugs he refused for help.

29.title: The Magic of Friction
29.plot: Cosmo finds himself a good-looking iron box when he is out scavenging. But how will he ever get this box all the way home?

30.title: Make Your Own Popcorn
30.plot: When the gang sees Rusty enjoying some popcorn for lunch, they decide to make some popcorn of their own.

31.title: When the Sun's Gone
31.plot: When Joe Croaker decides to celebrate his Pond-Claiming anniversary by bullying everyone around, Bartle Bee tricks him into thinking the sun will never rise again.

32.title: Sticky Strong Spider Web
32.plot: When a few of the insects of the marsh get themselves caught in a spiderweb, it is up to Bartle Bee to save them.

33.title: A Jewel Beetle's Recollection
33.plot: When a Jewel Beetle named Julie revisits the marsh after a long time away, he is shocked to see how much the marsh has changed. And to make matters worse, he doesn't even recognize his own reflection in the pond.

34.title: The Most Reliable Sensors
34.plot: Joe Croaker finds himself some chocolate. He eats one piece and hides the rest in a hollowed tree trunk. The little ant, Rusty, follows the smell to this very trunk and he takes one piece away with him. When the frog comes back for his food stash, he finds one piece is missing. He transfers the chocolate to a place he believes much safer. But Rusty's antennae can easily detect the scent in the air. He discovers the chocolate and takes another one. Joe Croaker now has good reason to believe there's a food thief around.

35.title: Just Like Bartle Bee
35.plot: When a mischievous Bartle Bee look-alike comes to the marsh, he causes all sorts of trouble for the rest of the insects. And, of course, Bartle Bee gets blamed.

36.title: Cosmo and His Coffee Beans
36.plot: After eating a bunch of coffee beans before bed, Cosmo the fly cannot fall asleep. He turns to his insect pals for help.

37.title: When Cosmo Lost His Touch
37.plot: When Cosmo the fly gets honey stuck on his hands, suddenly everything to him tastes like honey. He starts to eat some pretty unusual things, and it's up to his insect pals to figure out what's wrong with him.

38.title: When Strobe Stops Glowing
38.plot: When Strobe the firefly gets mud logged in his abdomen, he loses the ability to emit light. This is a form of retribution for his younger brother Sparkle who often gets teased by Strobe because his light was never quite as powerful.

39.title: The Trick of Atmospheric Pressure
39.plot: Joe Croaker finds a jar of some delicious juice. But when he sticks his head in the jar to suck out the last drops of juice, he gets stuck, and it's up to the insects he so often bullies to get him out.

40.title: A Natural Gardener
40.plot: Bartle Bee introduces his old friend Earwig to his fellow crawlies in the Marsh, but he did not expect Earwig would bring him so much trouble. It seems Earwig is a little too playful for a guy who has pair of "scissors" attached to his abdomen.

41.title: An Extraordinary Dancer
41.plot: When Flutterby finds a special plant that can dance, it becomes the hit of the marsh.

42.title: A Convenient Arch Bridge
42.plot: When Mc Broom the dung-beetle finds a huge cavern between his dung-balls and his home, he looks to the other insects of the marsh for help building a bridge.

43.title: The Trapped Dragonfly Nymph
43.plot: When Joe Croaker drives off a couple of dragonflies who were guarding their eggs, Cosmo the fly takes it upon himself to be the new protector of the eggs. Once the eggs hatch, however, even Joe gets in on the protecting.

44.title: Invasion and Counterattack
44.plot: When an amazon snail comes to the marsh and butters Joe Croaker up with a few compliments, he is welcomed with open arms. That is until he starts eating all the surrounding greenery and fills the pond with waste.

45.title: Fly with a Dandelion Seed
45.plot: When Rusty the and sees the other bugs flying, he becomes very jealous. He finds comfort in taking care of a dandelion. Can this dandelion help Rusty to fly?

46.title: The Puzzle Inside Chestnuts
46.plot: Strobe is surprised to find only empty shells where his chestnuts should be. Him and Bartle Bee find out that it is a Chestnut Weevil, but before they can get their revenge, he explains why chestnut weevils need chestnuts in their life.

47.title: The Sound of Tidal Waves
47.plot: The sound of the ocean is something a couple of marsh insects have never heard. That is until a conch shell finds its way to their home.

48.title: The Ingenuity of Deciduous Tress
48.plot: When Strobe and Sparkle find their favorite tree shedding leaves, they think it is sick.

49.title: How to Treat a Hiccup
49.plot: When Joe Croaker gets a bad case of the hiccups, he goes to Cosmo and Bartle Bee for help.

50.title: The Giant Water Lilies
50.plot: Joe Croaker notices there is an unusual lotus leaf in the pond and he clearly does not like it. And when the same water lily "attacks" Bartle Bee, he and Joe decide to try and get rid o f it. But how can they when every time they turn their heads, it grows bigger and bigger?

51.title: A Sweet Instinct
51.plot: When Cosmo the fly realizes that Rusty the ant is much better at locating sugar in the wild than he is, he decides to get to the bottom of it.

52.title: A Stubborn Icicle
52.plot: Joe Croaker and Cosmo are playing in the newly fallen snow. Everything is going smoothly until Joe sees an Icicle and decides to lick it. Now it's up to Cosmo to save the day.

53.title: When the Ants Start Moving
53.plot: Joe Croaker sees Rusty and his follow ants relocating. He takes this as an indication of approaching rain. The frog starts to warn every marsh inhabitant of the rain and at the same time he hurries home to take shelter. It is a very cloudy day and Joe is quite convinced that the rain will come soon. But when it never comes, he gets angry at Rusty.

54.title: The "Angry" Seed Pods
54.plot: When Joe Croaker notices that Flutterby's flowers are starting to bud, he claims them for himself. But the buds are not all they're cracked up to be.

55.title: Shi Fu Praying Mantis
55.plot: Cosmo snatches a peanut from the firefly Sparkle. A praying mantis sees this and he stands up for Sparkle. When the mantis hears Cosmo refuses to give the peanut back, he uses his agility to take it away. Cosmo tries to get back but the fly is simply no match for the mantis. This is until he gets a little help from his fly friend, Copper Top.

56.title: The Ear of a Log
56.plot: When the dead logs littering the marsh sprout ear-shaped fungus, Cosmo the Fly mistakes them for real ears.

57.title: A Rising Shelter
57.plot: Rusty is transporting the food when the rain comes. He takes shelter in a metal can and falls asleep there. When the little ant wakes up, he is surprised to find the can is in the air, hanging from a fast-growing bamboo shoot.

58.title: Beehive Engineering
58.plot: When Strobe and Sparkle are roughhousing near Bartle Bee's hive, they accidentally but a hole through it. They decide to repair it before Bartle Bee returns home, but what is a bee hive made of?

59.title: A Fish That Hops on Land
59.plot: When a mud-skipper visits the pond, he quickly makes enemies with some of the bugs by claiming a found piece of bread for his own. But when a tragedy gives him a chance to save the day, he goes from zero to hero.

60.title: The Truth About Geckos' Eyes
60.plot: Cosmo the Fly suffers a few sleepless nights protecting a colorful bouncy ball he found from Joe Croaker. But at least while he's awake, he learns the truth about geckos... they look like they sleep with their eyes open because of a protective transparent membrane that acts as an eyelid.

61.title: Heat Stroke for the Frog
61.plot: When Joe plays a little too hard on a hot summer day, he gets hit with heatstroke. It's now up to the same bugs he constantly bullies to save his hide.

62.title: Living Room or Oven
62.plot: It is an unusually hot day and most of the crawlies stay at home to avoid the unforgiving sun. But the fly Cosmo finds it is sweltering and suffocating to be inside his house, which is a metal can. He looks to the other bugs to find out why his house becomes an oven in the heat.

63.title: A Tiny Bird Is Still a Bird
63.plot: When a hummingbird visits the marsh, no one believes he is actually a bird. When he tries to prove it with flight, his unorthodox flight patterns only help to further dissuade them. How can he prove he is really a bird?

64.title: How a Pigeon Navigates
64.plot: A homing pigeon stops by the Marsh and asks Cosmo if he could rest there for a while before he continues his journey. Cosmo agrees, but only if the pigeon can beat him in a navigation competition.

65.title: Effortless Rolling
65.plot: When Cosmo the Fly finds a fancy new cart, he designates himself the delivery guy of the marsh. But when one of the wheels breaks on the cart, he must find a replacement wheel. What can he use?

66.title: How to Take Care of Flowers
66.plot: When Cosmo finds a cool looking flower in the marsh, Joe Croaker claims it for his own. He won't let anyone near it, even Flutterby, the designated flower expert of the marsh. but when the flower starts to die, Joe has no choice but to let Flutterby near his precious.

67.title: A Remarkable Leaf Mimic
67.plot: On an unusually hot day at the marsh, Bartle Bee decides to fan himself with a leaf from a tree. But when he goes to grab one, it screams. The poor leaf insect just wants some privacy, why does everyone keep grabbing him?

68.title: Outsized But Not Outwitted
68.plot: Joe Croaker steps on a Dwarf Frog. The Dwarf Frog asks Joe to apologize but Joe refuses to do so. When the Dwarf Frog comes across Cosmo and Rusty and learns that he is not the only victim of Joe's bullying, the tiny amphibian becomes angry. He decides to teach Joe a real lesson.

69.title: Warm Up a Little
69.plot: It's spring time and the temperature of the marsh is fluctuating greatly. This causes Flutterby to experience moments of extreme fatigue, and it's up to her insect pals to find out why.

70.title: Joe Croaker and Puffballs
70.plot: When Bartle Bee is returning from his mushroom gathering, Joe Croaker stops him and steals all the mushrooms for himself. Joe then decided to go find some more by himself, but mushroom hunting is something that should be left to the professionals.

71.title: Teach a Crab to Walk Straight
71.plot: After getting pinched by a local crab, Joe Croaker decides to get even by forcing the crab to walk straight.

72.title: A Fly in Amber
72.plot: Cosmo leaves the Marsh to visit his cousin who lives at the dump. Joe Croaker feels lonely without Cosmo around, so he goes to look for his buddy. On the way, he stumbles on a "stone" standing in his way. To his great surprise, he finds Cosmo is trapped inside. Or is it Cosmo?

73.title: A Tree That Generates Electricity
73.plot: When Joe Croaker gets electrocuted by a tree that keeps getting struck by lightning, Cosmo the Fly decided to touch it himself. The tree does not electrocute him, so he deems the tree his protector.

74.title: Against a Long-Horned Beetle
74.plot: A long-horned beetle comes to Marsh and saws off many twigs with his sharp teeth. With the help of Bartle Bee, Joe Croaker decides to stop this trouble maker.

75.title: Magnificent Is My First Name
75.plot: When a trouble-making spider comes to the marsh, he is quick to get on everyone's nerves. But when he accidentally uses his web to help Flutterby, no one is more surprised than him.

76.title: An Athlete in the Air
76.plot: When a mosquito decides to practice his flying over Cosmo's home, Cosmo is shocked to find that the mosquito is better at flying than he is. So he looks to Joe Croaker for help in driving this pest away.

77.title: Joe Croaker's Magic
77.plot: When a digital camera is found in the marsh, it isn't long before Joe Croaker realizes he can use the powerful flash as a weapon.

78.title: A Tree That Smiles
78.plot: Joe Croaker decides to mess up McBroom's dung-balls and Bartle Bee's honey. But when a mysterious tree seemingly laughs at him, he is scared into fixing everything back to the way he found them.

79.title: Plant-Louse Nymphs
79.plot: Rusty looks to Bartle Bee for help taking care of his colony's nymphs. Everything is going smoothly until a ladybug gang decides to steal the nymphs.

80.title: When Bamboo Finally Blooms
80.plot: When the gang decides to escape the summer heat by taking refuge in a nearby bamboo forest, they are shocked to see that the bamboo is dying. Not only that, but it is also producing flowers. They go to Niddy the Spider for an explanation.

81.title: Fly High in the Sky
81.plot: When an annoying kite finds its way into the marsh, Joe Croker does his best to get rid of it. But unfortunately it keeps flying back to him.

82.title: Magnifying Glass to Blame
82.plot: The gang finds a magnifying glass in the marsh. This amazing device allows them to see all sorts of wondrous things at night, but during the day, it turns into a mini death-ray of concentrated sunlight.

83.title: Hear with Wings
83.plot: When Joe Croaker steals all of Cosmo the Fly's hard-earned snacks, Cosmo demands an apology. But all he gets is a smack to his face. The smack damages his wings, and suddenly he can't hear anything. Why is that?

84.title: Better Hop Than Walk
84.plot: A sparrow comes to visit the Marsh. On his way around, he meets Bartle Bee who asks him why he hops rather than walks. To cover up the fact that he's unable to walk, the sparrow lies and says it's to build make more powerful legs. Being a curious little bee, Bartle Bee decides to learn to hop himself.

85.title: Where's the Great Musician?
85.plot: Sparkle is attracted to some fascinating music on his way to collect morning dew. He tracks the tune to a cricket and mistakes it for a musician. The cricket tells Sparkle he's got the wrong guy, but it would be his pleasure to look for the mysterious musician together with Sparkle.

86.title: A Fragile Tail
86.plot: A gecko loses its deeply loved tail in a "dung ball accident" caused by McBroom. Being remorseful for the accident, McBroom goes to visit the little gecko with some delicious food but is refused by the sorrowful victim. Mc Broom feels very upset and frustrated, and doesn't know what to do. How can he make it up to him?

87.title: The Molting of a Cicada
87.plot: When Cosmo the Fly decides to tease a visiting cicada about being flightless, the cicada vows that one day he's fly circles around Cosmo.

88.title: Autumn Heat
88.plot: An unusually weathered autumn forces Joe Croaker and Bartle Bee to seek shade during the sweltering days, and huddle by a campfire during the freezing nights.

89.title: The Wonder of Metamorphosis
89.plot: Cosmo meets Quinn, a tadpole in Joe Croaker's pond, and they become good friends. As time goes by, Quinn undergoes an amazing metamorphosis and grows into a frog.

90.title: An Easy Telephone Network
90.plot: A voice coming from a mysterious talking box invites Flutterby to visit Niddy. At Niddy's house, Bartle Bee shows Flutterby his latest invention: a makeshift telephone system. The two decides to install the device in every home in the Marsh.

91.title: An Unbreakable Stone
91.plot: When the firefly brothers, Strobe and Sparkle, find a diamond in the marsh, it isn't long before the devilish Cosmo hatches a plan to steal it.

92.title: Inside a Water Lily Flower
92.plot: Flutterby finds a beautiful waterlily in the pond and stops to collect nectar from it. She is so tired afterword that she falls asleep in the flower. When she wakes up, she finds she's been locked inside the flower, and it's up to Bartle Bee to get her out.

93.title: Sunflowers
93.plot: Joe Croaker and Cosmo hide their food under the same sunflower in the morning. Joe buries a jar of honey right in front of the flower while Cosmo buries a jar of popcorn right behind it. But when the sunflower starts following the sun in the sky, suddenly it's hard to tell what is the front and what is the back.

94.title: Thanks to the Cylinder
94.plot: Joe Croakers wants to build a high platform so that he can lie down on it to stare up at the stars at night. He finds a heavy plank but still needs a pole to support it. He tries a couple of posts in different shapes but not one of them are strong enough to support the plank. After having failed several times, the frog gets very frustrated. Inspired by a tree trunk, Bartle Bee suggests that Joe use a cylinder.

95.title: Battery Pollution
95.plot: Joe Croaker stumbles on a used battery. He gets so irritated that he smashes the battery and kicks it away into the pond. The chemical fluid from the broken battery causes a reaction in the pond that turns the water mucky and stinky. What should he do now?

96.title: A Stink Bug!
96.plot: When Cosmo gets bullied by Joe Croaker yet again, he complains to a new insect in the marsh - a stinkbug. The Stinkbug decides to pay Joe back with his secret weapon - farting.

97.title: How Strong an Ant Can Be?
97.plot: Cosmo and Rusty find a piece of bread together. Rusty suggests they split it 50-50, but Cosmo wants it all to himself. After having judged the size of the little ant, Cosmo proposes that they have a strength contest, and the winner takes home the whole piece of bread. Silly Cosmo.

98.title: A Most Precise Radar
98.plot: A friendly bat visits the marsh and it isn't long before a game of hide-and-seek is initiated. But much to everyone's dismay, the bat is far superior at the game thanks to his radar.

99.title: Termite Facts
99.plot: When a little termite loses his way in the Marsh, the hospitable Niddy takes the new comer home and treats him to some fresh fruit. Not interested in fruit, the hungry termite eats Niddy's wooden cane while she's out working on her web. What else is this little bugger going to eat?

100.title: The Leafless Grass
100.plot: When a mysterious green stalk starts sprouting in the middle of Flutterby's flower garden, she turns to Bartle Bee and Niddy to figure out what this intruder is really about.

101.title: A Light-Sensitive Flower
101.plot: Bartle Bee hides his honey jar in a red flower in the morning. When he comes back for his honey at lunch time, to his surprise, the flower is missing. He searches all the flowers in the area but there's no sign the red one he hid his honey in. Did it disappear?

102.title: A Wall-Running Expert
102.plot: Joe Croakers brags before Cosmo and a little gecko that he can withstand the strongest wind. However, he and Cosmo are blown away by a big wind but the little gecko stays put on a stone. How can this be?

103.title: Stop Buzzing!
103.plot: Joe Croaker is harassed by a buzzing mosquito. So Joe decides to do a little harassing of his own.

104.title: Stable Triangles
104.plot: When the firefly brothers, Strobe and Sparkle, decide to build a seesaw, they get hung up in what to use for a base. They go to Bartle Bee for help who suggests some type of triangle.

imdb.plot outline: Wouldn't it be great fun for an animated series to focus on the lively workings of the insect world, just as children started exploring the wonders of nature for themselves? Brainy Bubbly Bug Buddies, Fantawild's new 104-episode series, spins charming tales from the woods to the wetlands, spotlighting a bustling colony of creepy-crawlies-and the cheerfully troublesome frog they count as neighbor and friend. Amid the insect-adventures, audiences will get a bug's-eye view of the habits and habitats of actual insects of many kinds, and will learn how these creatures thrive in their environments. Imagine children everywhere sitting down to be entertained, and getting up with a new understanding of the world around them! In Brainy Bubbly Bug Buddies, characters thrive in a lush wetland paradise. Among its inhabitants are Bartle Bee, the fencing-master bumblebee; Flutterby, the elegant butterfly; Strobe and Sparkle, the heart-of-gold firefly brothers; and McBroom, the hardest-working beetle in the land. The Marsh is always buzzing with activity, and little viewers will be captivated by the lively blend of action and discovery to be found in its colorful environs. Our exoskeletal heroes bring their collective skills and ingenuity to bear on life's challenges in The Marsh, and in the end, they are rewarded for their efforts. Young learners are thus reminded that problem-solving is often best accomplished as a joint effort-and, coincidentally, that we live in a vast world worthy of exploration at even the most minute level of existence. Regular visits to The Marsh will delight and intrigue, all while nurturing children's budding quest for knowledge-and imbuing them with a healthy respect for life in the natural realm.
